The endangered Australian Sea Lion (Neophoca cinerea) is today found only in coastal western and southern Australia. However, fossil evidence indicates a close relative of this species once inhabited the North Island of New Zealand, the extinct Neophoca palatina. However, few studies have compared this species to other living fur seals and sea lions. Further study of this species is important, as it remains one of the very few fossil sea lions known from the Australasian region, and may provide important clues on the evolution of southern hemisphere fur seals and sea lions. My study looked at 170 skulls of sea lions and fur seals from throughout the Australian and New Zealand region. Using 44 cranial measurements we confirmed a close relationship between Neophoca palatina and the living Australian sea lion, as well as confirming it was a distinct species from the living form. The presence of this fossil species in New Zealand, which today is inhabited by two other species of fur seal and sea lion, indicates that New Zealand may have been an important center of diversification for fur seals and sea lions. Our study indicates that the ancestors of the Australian sea lion had a much wider distribution in the past, and that their current distribution is closely tied to climate. Future climate change is likely to influence the population of the Australian sea lions, and should be considered in conservation plans.




